1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
[UNKNOWN] Jeff Gotlieb:

2
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:12,000
[SPEAKER_02] Okay. Hello everyone. My name is Jeff Gotlieb. I'm with the International Monetary Fund.

3
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:21,000
[SPEAKER_02] I'm the IMF's res rep for Central and Eastern Europe, based in Warsaw, and I cover Central and Eastern Europe out of Warsaw.

4
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:27,000
[SPEAKER_02] It's great to be here, and thank you very much to the Croatian National Bank for the invitation.

5
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:33,000
[SPEAKER_02] The only thing more amazing than the beauty of Dubrovnik is how much of Croatia actually looks like this.

6
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:40,000
[SPEAKER_02] It's really not a one-stop, one-trick pony, and it's a good reason to keep Croatians close to you in life.

7
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:47,000
[SPEAKER_02] It's really great to be here, and I think labor is an excellent time to discuss the labor issue.

8
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:56,000
[SPEAKER_02] As many of you know, there were two main ways that much of the profession got the inflation thing wrong.

9
00:00:56,000 --> 00:01:02,000
[SPEAKER_02] The first one was to not expect inflation to be such a problem in the first place.

10
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:07,000
[SPEAKER_02] The second one was that even if you did think that there was too much demand and it was going to come to inflation,

11
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:14,000
[SPEAKER_02] many people thought that it would come through wages and tension in the labor market, not through goods, which is what we've seen.

12
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:23,000
[SPEAKER_02] So thus far, the labor market has not been the key player in the inflation process, but now it seems like things are turning.

13
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:28,000
[SPEAKER_02] So the initial shock has started to fade in terms of the components.

14
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:30,000
[SPEAKER_02] The labor market is still very tight.

15
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:32,000
[SPEAKER_02] Core inflation is very high.

16
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:41,000
[SPEAKER_02] So when I talk to policymakers, most of them seem to agree that to the degree they get inflation wrong going forward,

17
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:45,000
[SPEAKER_02] it might be because they're misestimating what is happening in the labor market.

18
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:52,000
[SPEAKER_02] So just to frame the discussion for my colleagues here today, I'll just briefly touch on three questions.

19
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:55,000
[SPEAKER_02] Where are we now and why?

20
00:01:55,000 --> 00:01:56,000
[SPEAKER_02] Where are we going?

21
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:00,000
[SPEAKER_02] And what should policymakers do about it?

22
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:08,000
[SPEAKER_02] So on the first, when we talk about labor market resilience, we're usually talking about the quantity side, basically employment.

23
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:11,000
[SPEAKER_02] And there's two parts of this story.

24
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:17,000
[SPEAKER_02] The first is the vacancy unemployment story, where we basically saw a shift up in the beverage curve.

25
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:22,000
[SPEAKER_02] People have different reasons for this, from matching to people leaving the labor force.

26
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:29,000
[SPEAKER_02] But this is the key reason that people think the unemployment rate understates the true tightness in the labor market.

27
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:38,000
[SPEAKER_02] The second, which is a bit less discussed, is that employment growth is actually positive in many of the major and emerging market economies.

28
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:45,000
[SPEAKER_02] So it's not a story where employment is falling, but slowly, or employment is steady and there's hoarding.

29
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:52,000
[SPEAKER_02] We have a situation where even with falling output, we have firms adding employees.

30
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:55,000
[SPEAKER_02] So you see a fall in labor productivity.

31
00:02:55,000 --> 00:03:00,000
[SPEAKER_02] You can come up with a variety of stories for this, but labor productivity growth in many countries is negative,

32
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:02,000
[SPEAKER_02] depending exactly on how you measure it.

33
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:06,000
[SPEAKER_02] So well below trend, and surprisingly so.

34
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:07,000
[SPEAKER_02] It can't be sustained.

35
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:12,000
[SPEAKER_02] Either you would expect output to start to recover, or employment to fall.

36
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:17,000
[SPEAKER_02] But now moving on to the price side, wages.

37
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:20,000
[SPEAKER_02] Wages, as I said, have not been a big player.

38
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:23,000
[SPEAKER_02] You wouldn't describe them as wildly resilient.

39
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:30,000
[SPEAKER_02] So as many people have cited, in advanced economies, real wages are negative.

40
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:36,000
[SPEAKER_02] In emerging markets, they're a bit closer to even, but they have turned negative in the last two quarters.

41
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:45,000
[SPEAKER_02] And so you have an inflation process where, consistent with maybe what you would expect, prices have been far more flexible than wages.

42
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:52,000
[SPEAKER_02] So if you decompose inflation thus far, you see a big increase in imported prices.

43
00:03:52,000 --> 00:04:04,000
[SPEAKER_02] You see a big increase in markups by firms, and that has led to the inflation, while real wages have remained negative to flat, resulting in high corporate profits.

44
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:08,000
[SPEAKER_02] So again, this resilience story, I think one needs to separate.

45
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:19,000
[SPEAKER_02] And depending on the country, in some cases the employment story I talked about has overwhelmed the negative real wage story, keeping demand overall strong.

46
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:25,000
[SPEAKER_02] But again, I think it's important to separate these two, and I'll come back to that on the policy recommendation side.

47
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:28,000
[SPEAKER_02] Okay, the second part is where we go from here.

48
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:31,000
[SPEAKER_02] And there's kind of two broad stories.

49
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:41,000
[SPEAKER_02] There's a benign scenario, which is where this vacancy unemployment rate issue solves itself, in kind of a soft landing respect.

50
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:50,000
[SPEAKER_02] Which is basically that, rather than the vacancy unemployment ratio reflecting a deep matching problem, that might need a big increase in unemployment to solve.

51
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:57,000
[SPEAKER_02] You basically have people come back to the labor force, and vacancies come down, without a rise in the unemployment rate.

52
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:00,000
[SPEAKER_02] And so you get less concerned about the tightness of the labor market.

53
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:05,000
[SPEAKER_02] The second component is that you do get some increase in unemployment.

54
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:12,000
[SPEAKER_02] So basically, you have weaker pricing power by firms consistent with the slowing economy.

55
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:14,000
[SPEAKER_02] You get rising real wages.

56
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:17,000
[SPEAKER_02] These two components drive profits down.

57
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:20,000
[SPEAKER_02] And eventually, you see some uptick in unemployment.

58
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:30,000
[SPEAKER_02] So if you got these two components, basically a fall in the vacancy unemployment ratio, some increase in unemployment because of the slowing economy and profit margins.

59
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:37,000
[SPEAKER_02] Combined with no new shocks, that would be an environment in which I think we would all feel more comfortable about the inflation pressures.

60
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:43,000
[SPEAKER_02] But then there's also a significantly -- there's a less benign scenario, basically.

61
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:48,000
[SPEAKER_02] I mean, one is that our star, to reference the previous presentation, is different from where we thought.

62
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:51,000
[SPEAKER_02] So monetary policy is not as tight as we thought.

63
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:54,000
[SPEAKER_02] The credit cycle turns.

64
00:05:54,000 --> 00:05:57,000
[SPEAKER_02] Pricing power is weaker than what we thought.

65
00:05:57,000 --> 00:06:06,000
[SPEAKER_02] Basically, profits stay somewhat high, and you're able to pass on higher prices, and inflation stays much stronger.

66
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:10,000
[SPEAKER_02] At the same time, perhaps, we're exposed to new shocks.

67
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:18,000
[SPEAKER_02] And it's -- there's obviously other scenarios, but these are kind of a benign and a much less benign scenario for where we go from here.

68
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:24,000
[SPEAKER_02] But I think there's -- there's lots of questions in between those two scenarios.

69
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:31,000
[SPEAKER_02] So just one last comment on -- in terms of what this all means for policymakers.

70
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:39,000
[SPEAKER_02] I think outside of the profession and conferences like this, the framing about the labor market is not about resilience.

71
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:43,000
[SPEAKER_02] So in the newspaper, it would be framed far more negatively.

72
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:49,000
[SPEAKER_02] It would be framed as a cost of living crisis, combined with extremely high corporate profits.

73
00:06:49,000 --> 00:07:00,000
[SPEAKER_02] And I think that this angle, rather than the more positive angle of labor market resilience, is very important to consider for two reasons.

74
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:06,000
[SPEAKER_02] One, on its own front, I think we need to be aware of the distributional consequences.

75
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:13,000
[SPEAKER_02] There is the temporary issues of cost of living, and there's the more structural issue of the labor share of income.

76
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:19,000
[SPEAKER_02] And I think that this is a fair angle that policymakers should be considering.

77
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:34,000
[SPEAKER_02] The second is a bit more pernicious, which is that -- and I've had this in conversations with policymakers so far -- it's possible to take that diagnosis and get to policies that, at least we would think, are far more dangerous.

78
00:07:34,000 --> 00:07:46,000
[SPEAKER_02] Which is that the angle can be put that this is not something for monetary policy to do, but it's something for finance ministries and regulators to attack profits directly.

79
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:55,000
[SPEAKER_02] And this can lead to consequences that ultimately don't address the underlying inflation problem while still compromising the fiscal.

80
00:07:55,000 --> 00:08:05,000
[SPEAKER_02] So we can maybe come back to some of those issues, but I think that this framing, both the macroeconomic, how much tightness do we need to address the inflation problem,

81
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:14,000
[SPEAKER_02] and the more distributional issue of how we make sure that labor is supported over the course of this crisis, is important to consider.

82
00:08:14,000 --> 00:08:19,000
[SPEAKER_02] So I will stop there and pass to our first speaker, Christian Kopp.

83
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:25,000
[SPEAKER_03] Christian Kopp: Yes, thanks very much.

84
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:28,000
[SPEAKER_03] Great honor to be invited again to Dubrovnik.

85
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:41,000
[SPEAKER_03] So I have -- I'm going to follow the agenda that Joff laid out, and start out with where are we now, and then have three thoughts on where we're going,

86
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:44,000
[SPEAKER_03] and then maybe just one thought on what to do.

87
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:45,000
[SPEAKER_03] So where are we now?

88
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:52,000
[SPEAKER_03] I think the resilience of the labor market, first thought, has something to do with the strength of the service economy.

89
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:58,000
[SPEAKER_03] And you can see that here in the picture from the beautiful dinner we had last night.

90
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:03,000
[SPEAKER_03] That is one of the reasons why we have such a resilient and strong labor market.

91
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:08,000
[SPEAKER_03] Now, in the short run, it is true that the labor market is surprisingly strong.

92
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:14,000
[SPEAKER_03] We just heard in the previous presentation that we had a 200 basis point shock to real interest rates in most advanced economies.

93
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:26,000
[SPEAKER_03] And I think most in the room, including myself, would not have expected such a resilient labor market in the face of that up drift in real interest rates.

94
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:33,000
[SPEAKER_03] So we have in the U.S. an unemployment rate of 3.4 percent, which is the lowest level since 1969.

95
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:38,000
[SPEAKER_03] And in the Euro area, we have an unemployment rate of 8.5 percent, which is the lowest level on record.

96
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:48,000
[SPEAKER_03] Even if you go back to the pre-Euro area period, we haven't had an 8.5 percent unemployment rate, I believe, probably since the 1950s or '60s.

97
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:51,000
[SPEAKER_03] So it's a very resilient labor market.

98
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:59,000
[SPEAKER_03] And if you look at the U.S., the early indicators on the labor market are not really pointing to a rapid decline in employment growth.

99
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:05,000
[SPEAKER_03] We still have a lot of job openings, a lot of positions which companies are unable to fill.

100
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:10,000
[SPEAKER_03] So then on the short run, two more thoughts.

101
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:14,000
[SPEAKER_03] I think there is an element of labor hoarding, especially in the United States.

102
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:25,000
[SPEAKER_03] So what I'm plotting here is the change in the private sector employment and the final sales to domestic consumers in constant prices.

103
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:33,000
[SPEAKER_03] And you can see that the growth rate of the final sales to domestic consumers is much higher than the employment growth on trend.

104
00:10:33,000 --> 00:10:37,000
[SPEAKER_03] And that is indicative of labor productivity growth.

105
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:39,000
[SPEAKER_03] But you don't have that since the pandemic.

106
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:43,000
[SPEAKER_03] So index that back to December 2019.

107
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:48,000
[SPEAKER_03] We can see that both time series are growing to the same extent.

108
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:57,000
[SPEAKER_03] So that could be indicative of labor hoarding because, you know, I'd be surprised if productivity growth had suddenly fallen to zero.

109
00:10:57,000 --> 00:11:04,000
[SPEAKER_03] So I think that there is an element here of U.S. companies being unable to find the workers they need in the market.

110
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:11,000
[SPEAKER_03] And therefore they are deciding to hold on to those workers because they feel that they were not able to find them again if they fire them now.

111
00:11:11,000 --> 00:11:13,000
[SPEAKER_03] Now that may at one point in time unravel.

112
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:21,000
[SPEAKER_03] And there is a risk that if we do see a continuation of very weak domestic sales growth in the U.S.

113
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:26,000
[SPEAKER_03] At one point in time, all of those U.S. companies at the same time start to, you know, fire people.

114
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:27,000
[SPEAKER_03] And then that could backfire.

115
00:11:27,000 --> 00:11:30,000
[SPEAKER_03] But for the time being, there is some labor hoarding here.

116
00:11:30,000 --> 00:11:36,000
[SPEAKER_03] And I hope that the economy will recover and companies can hold on to the people they have.

117
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:42,000
[SPEAKER_03] Now for the euro area, I don't think that we have an overheating labor market.

118
00:11:42,000 --> 00:11:46,000
[SPEAKER_03] These are two charts that I borrowed from Robin Brooks at the IAF.

119
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:55,000
[SPEAKER_03] And you can see on the left-hand side the changes in core prices versus the changes in wages.

120
00:11:55,000 --> 00:12:04,000
[SPEAKER_03] And you can see that in most countries wage inflation is lower than core inflation in the euro area with the exception of Belgium and Greece for whatever reason.

121
00:12:04,000 --> 00:12:06,000
[SPEAKER_03] So we really don't have a wage price spiral here.

122
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:13,000
[SPEAKER_03] I think core inflation in the euro area is driven by other factors, probably by profit inflation, but not so much by wage inflation.

123
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:23,000
[SPEAKER_03] And then another reason why I don't really think that we're facing an overheating EU labor market has to do with the labor force participation rates.

124
00:12:23,000 --> 00:12:32,000
[SPEAKER_03] And you can see that the employment to population ratio in most countries in the euro area is still below the previous peak, which was achieved in 2007.

125
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:39,000
[SPEAKER_03] So I don't really think that we have an overheating labor market here, with a few exceptions.

126
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:41,000
[SPEAKER_03] Maybe in Germany we have an element of that.

127
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:47,000
[SPEAKER_03] But most other countries still have scope to increase the employment ratios.

128
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:49,000
[SPEAKER_03] Now that's the short run.

129
00:12:49,000 --> 00:12:56,000
[SPEAKER_03] And the long run, here I would like to borrow an analysis that Daniel Gross has just presented, has just published.

130
00:12:56,000 --> 00:13:02,000
[SPEAKER_03] And that looks at the structural changes in the labor force participation rate.

131
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:06,000
[SPEAKER_03] And what Daniel has done here, he's here in the room, and he'll speak later on.

132
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:15,000
[SPEAKER_03] What Daniel has done here is he has attributed or he has related those changes in employment to changes in the education level.

133
00:13:15,000 --> 00:13:22,000
[SPEAKER_03] And it turns out that population cohorts with high levels of inflation tend to have a high level of education.

134
00:13:22,000 --> 00:13:30,000
[SPEAKER_03] And the increase in the educational achievement levels can explain around two-thirds of the increase in the EU labor force participation rate.

135
00:13:30,000 --> 00:13:45,000
[SPEAKER_03] So I think that the increase in employment, basically, you know, it's not that we had a lot of idle people before, especially women who were not part of the labor market.

136
00:13:45,000 --> 00:13:49,000
[SPEAKER_03] But what we're talking about here is labor market.

137
00:13:49,000 --> 00:13:58,000
[SPEAKER_03] So once you enter into, you know, into the division of labor, into formal employment, you need to have some form of specialization.

138
00:13:58,000 --> 00:14:01,000
[SPEAKER_03] If you do reproductive work at home, you're not idle.

139
00:14:01,000 --> 00:14:07,000
[SPEAKER_03] You do a lot of different things, you know, childcare, looking after whatever, you know, things in the household.

140
00:14:07,000 --> 00:14:17,000
[SPEAKER_03] But in order to become part of the formal labor market, I think you need some form of formal education in order to be able to contribute to this division of labor.

141
00:14:17,000 --> 00:14:21,000
[SPEAKER_03] And we see that the levels of formal education are rising rapidly in the EU area.

142
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:25,000
[SPEAKER_03] And the consequence of that, we also see an increase in the employment to population ratio.

143
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:33,000
[SPEAKER_03] So the longer run trend of the resilience of the labor market has to do with the fact that with the increase in education levels,

144
00:14:33,000 --> 00:14:37,000
[SPEAKER_03] with the participation in the labor market increases on trend.

145
00:14:37,000 --> 00:14:40,000
[SPEAKER_03] And that, I think, is something that will continue.

146
00:14:40,000 --> 00:14:48,000
[SPEAKER_03] The second point is related to the fact that we face very different patterns in different countries.

147
00:14:48,000 --> 00:14:53,000
[SPEAKER_03] So I've picked out three countries here, Hungary, Czech Republic, and Germany.

148
00:14:53,000 --> 00:14:56,000
[SPEAKER_03] And you can see that each one of those countries has very different patterns.

149
00:14:56,000 --> 00:15:02,000
[SPEAKER_03] You know, in Hungary and in the Czech Republic, we had a decline in employment in the years,

150
00:15:02,000 --> 00:15:09,000
[SPEAKER_03] following, you know, the end of communism because of the economic transformation.

151
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:14,000
[SPEAKER_03] And that, in the beginning, led to negative employment and growth.

152
00:15:14,000 --> 00:15:18,000
[SPEAKER_03] What also happened is that in Hungary, at least, we had negative employment growth --

153
00:15:18,000 --> 00:15:23,000
[SPEAKER_03] sorry, negative labor force growth because we had a lot of outbound migration from Hungary.

154
00:15:23,000 --> 00:15:27,000
[SPEAKER_03] Now, Czech Republic is one of the countries that stands out for not having had that outbound migration.

155
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:32,000
[SPEAKER_03] But I think in most CE countries -- I'll show that in the following slide -- we had that outbound migration,

156
00:15:32,000 --> 00:15:36,000
[SPEAKER_03] which is a big contributor to the tightness in the labor market.

157
00:15:36,000 --> 00:15:48,000
[SPEAKER_03] And then from 2000 -- you know, I suppose from 2010 onwards, we've had this rapid increase in employment in all Central European countries,

158
00:15:48,000 --> 00:15:53,000
[SPEAKER_03] which to some extent was export-driven, you know, so you have a very rapid increase there.

159
00:15:53,000 --> 00:16:03,000
[SPEAKER_03] And that now leads to a situation where we have relatively tight labor markets in Central and Eastern Europe and the need to attract an inflow of migrant workers,

160
00:16:03,000 --> 00:16:09,000
[SPEAKER_03] which is something that we discussed here yesterday and which leads to problems in many of those countries.

161
00:16:09,000 --> 00:16:11,000
[SPEAKER_03] Now, Poland has had it easier.

162
00:16:11,000 --> 00:16:15,000
[SPEAKER_03] They've been able to attract people from Ukraine and Belarus even before the crisis.

163
00:16:15,000 --> 00:16:20,000
[SPEAKER_03] Other countries, such as Hungary, are having a tougher time increasing the labor force.

164
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:26,000
[SPEAKER_03] And that has to do with some of the things we discussed -- which Joel Mocker discussed here yesterday,

165
00:16:26,000 --> 00:16:36,000
[SPEAKER_03] that he said phenotypical differences can lead to -- how did he put it -- there was a word that he used.

166
00:16:36,000 --> 00:16:41,000
[SPEAKER_03] It was not racism, yeah, but it was -- homophilia.

167
00:16:41,000 --> 00:16:42,000
[SPEAKER_03] Homophilia was the word.

168
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:43,000
[SPEAKER_03] Yeah, exactly.

169
00:16:43,000 --> 00:16:50,000
[SPEAKER_03] So I think some of the countries find it difficult to attract and to, you know, integrate foreign workers.

170
00:16:50,000 --> 00:16:52,000
[SPEAKER_03] And Hungary is a case in point.

171
00:16:52,000 --> 00:16:55,000
[SPEAKER_03] And as a result of that, you have a very tight labor market in some of those countries.

172
00:16:55,000 --> 00:17:02,000
[SPEAKER_03] Other countries have been more open to migrant flows, and that has helped to mitigate the tightness in the labor market.

173
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:08,000
[SPEAKER_03] Now, in Germany, you see a very strong rise in employment from 2005 onwards.

174
00:17:08,000 --> 00:17:10,000
[SPEAKER_03] And that was not related to migration.

175
00:17:10,000 --> 00:17:14,000
[SPEAKER_03] It was not related to economic transformation, but to a policy change.

176
00:17:14,000 --> 00:17:18,000
[SPEAKER_03] The HALS reforms were implemented in September 2003.

177
00:17:18,000 --> 00:17:24,000
[SPEAKER_03] And then from 2005 onwards, we've seen a rapid increase in employment because unemployment benefits were cut dramatically.

178
00:17:24,000 --> 00:17:31,000
[SPEAKER_03] by the German government, and that, you know, that contributed to this decline in the unemployment rate and also the rise in employment.

179
00:17:31,000 --> 00:17:36,000
[SPEAKER_03] So I think that, you know, the resilience of the labor market is a global phenomenon.

180
00:17:36,000 --> 00:17:43,000
[SPEAKER_03] Most of it can be attributed in advanced economies by structural changes, such as the increase in education achievements.

181
00:17:43,000 --> 00:17:52,000
[SPEAKER_03] And then within the individual countries, you have a lot of diversity, and the diversity is related to policy changes, such as, you know, labor market reforms.

182
00:17:52,000 --> 00:17:59,000
[SPEAKER_03] And also to, you know, the attitude towards migrant workers, which really differs from country to country.

183
00:17:59,000 --> 00:18:09,000
[SPEAKER_03] And here, there's another chart which shows the outbound migration, which has had a massive impact, especially in Eastern European countries.

184
00:18:09,000 --> 00:18:15,000
[SPEAKER_03] The chart that I borrowed from an analysis published by George Safari a couple of years ago.

185
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:27,000
[SPEAKER_03] And you can see the, you know, the big outflows that all of those Central European countries have seen, both as a share of their labor force and as a share of the economically active population.

186
00:18:27,000 --> 00:18:31,000
[SPEAKER_03] In Romania, it was dramatic, you know, the outflux of people.

187
00:18:31,000 --> 00:18:41,000
[SPEAKER_03] And the Czech Republic stands out as one of the few countries which hasn't had much of an outflow of workers following the fall of the communist regime, you know.

188
00:18:41,000 --> 00:18:46,000
[SPEAKER_03] So really, there seem to be big differences in the individual countries.

189
00:18:46,000 --> 00:18:48,000
[SPEAKER_03] Final point on where we are going.

190
00:18:48,000 --> 00:18:58,000
[SPEAKER_03] So the first point is that we have a structural increase in education, which is one of the reasons why we have a very resilient labor market and growing labor force participation.

191
00:18:58,000 --> 00:19:08,000
[SPEAKER_03] Second point is the diversity that we have in the different countries, which is related to policy choices and unemployment benefits and to migration flows.

192
00:19:08,000 --> 00:19:11,000
[SPEAKER_03] And the third point is a little bit looking forward.

193
00:19:11,000 --> 00:19:22,000
[SPEAKER_03] And that has, that's just a question, whether we are at the threshold of a new area of very strong productivity growth driven by the increased use of artificial intelligence.

194
00:19:22,000 --> 00:19:42,000
[SPEAKER_03] Just, you know, an anecdote, I read a report recently that programmers at Microsoft have seen an increase in the productivity of their work by 50% through the use of large language models such as, you know, the ones that have been popularized now in a very short period of time.

195
00:19:42,000 --> 00:19:50,000
[SPEAKER_03] So, you know, the coding has become much faster for them and the debugging is now done by those artificial intelligence models.

196
00:19:50,000 --> 00:19:58,000
[SPEAKER_03] Therefore, the output per hour worked for an individual computer program has increased by 50% in a matter of one or two years, yeah.

197
00:19:58,000 --> 00:20:03,000
[SPEAKER_03] So this is, of course, just a small segment of the population, of the economically active population.

198
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:16,000
[SPEAKER_03] But I think that we may be at the threshold, at the start of a new productivity cycle, which could also lead to, you know, labor savings in the years ahead.

199
00:20:16,000 --> 00:20:18,000
[SPEAKER_03] And it remains to be seen how this plays out.

200
00:20:18,000 --> 00:20:32,000
[SPEAKER_03] I mean, we can see that in the past, whenever there was a big increase in -- whenever there were big technological innovations, with a lag of two, three years, we've seen a trend increase in U.S. productivity growth.

201
00:20:32,000 --> 00:20:39,000
[SPEAKER_03] And we may be at, you know, at the start of another one of those eras, driven by artificial intelligence.

202
00:20:39,000 --> 00:20:42,000
[SPEAKER_03] And, you know, it remains to be seen how this will impact the labor market.

203
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:45,000
[SPEAKER_03] And then, final question on what to do, yeah.

204
00:20:45,000 --> 00:20:53,000
[SPEAKER_03] So I don't have a quote here on that, but frankly, I think that the developments that we're seeing are extremely positive, no?

205
00:20:53,000 --> 00:21:02,000
[SPEAKER_03] I mean, so we see a larger participation, especially of women in the labor force, yeah, driven by higher levels of education.

206
00:21:02,000 --> 00:21:10,000
[SPEAKER_03] And we have the chances, you know, all the opportunities that arise from the use of those technological innovations.

207
00:21:10,000 --> 00:21:15,000
[SPEAKER_03] Many of us have experienced that during the pandemic, that we can now work from home, yeah?

208
00:21:15,000 --> 00:21:22,000
[SPEAKER_03] I actually think that probably the productivity numbers which are published here underestimate the actual productivity growth.

209
00:21:22,000 --> 00:21:27,000
[SPEAKER_03] I mean, if I look at my office, yeah, people don't tend to work on Mondays and Fridays.

210
00:21:27,000 --> 00:21:32,000
[SPEAKER_03] They look at the computer from time to time, but they only come to the office three days a week.

211
00:21:32,000 --> 00:21:34,000
[SPEAKER_03] And they still get the same salary, yeah?

212
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:43,000
[SPEAKER_03] So I actually think, you know, the number of hours worked has -- the effective number of hours worked in those office jobs has declined substantially, yeah?

213
00:21:43,000 --> 00:21:47,000
[SPEAKER_03] And that probably doesn't show up in the national accounts or in the statistics.

214
00:21:47,000 --> 00:21:55,000
[SPEAKER_03] So we may have just seen a massive increase in productivity through this working from home and teleconferencing and all that kind of stuff.

215
00:21:55,000 --> 00:22:06,000
[SPEAKER_03] And I actually think that we're moving to a world which is, you know, pretty close to the world that Karl Marx has described in the German ideology,

216
00:22:06,000 --> 00:22:21,000
[SPEAKER_03] where in one famous paragraph he talks about communism as the status where you can be a hunter and a, you know, philosopher in the morning.

217
00:22:21,000 --> 00:22:28,000
[SPEAKER_03] You can be a hunter in the morning, you can be a philosopher in the afternoon, and you can do whatever else during the rest of the day.

218
00:22:28,000 --> 00:22:31,000
[SPEAKER_03] And you don't have to be confined to just one job, yeah?

219
00:22:31,000 --> 00:22:39,000
[SPEAKER_03] So I think that we're moving to a much more diverse, you know, working life and employment status,

220
00:22:39,000 --> 00:22:43,000
[SPEAKER_03] and one that will afford much greater liberties to most of us.

221
00:22:43,000 --> 00:22:46,000
[SPEAKER_03] So I think it's actually great development that lies ahead.

222
00:22:46,000 --> 00:22:47,000
[SPEAKER_03] Thank you.

223
00:22:47,000 --> 00:22:48,000
[SPEAKER_03] Thank you.

224
00:22:48,000 --> 00:23:17,980
[SPEAKER_00] Hvala vam.

225
00:23:18,000 --> 00:23:25,400
[SPEAKER_00] Good morning. Let me start by thanking Boris and the National Bank of Croatia for inviting me again to this very interesting conference.

226
00:23:25,400 --> 00:23:34,759
[SPEAKER_00] As a starter, I would also like to make two kavits. Not a customary institutional one, but more on substance.

227
00:23:34,759 --> 00:23:43,039
[SPEAKER_00] One is that I'm not a labor economist. There are people in the room who are, so they are potentially better placed to look into this issue.

228
00:23:43,039 --> 00:23:47,180
[SPEAKER_00] So I'm a macroeconomist and I look into the labor market from a macro perspective.

229
00:23:48,000 --> 00:24:03,220
[SPEAKER_00] And second, I will talk essentially about the European labor market, which doesn't exist because the European labor market is a patchwork of around 50 clusters of regional labor markets.

230
00:24:03,380 --> 00:24:17,200
[SPEAKER_00] So what I'm telling is very aggregated and generalized, but gives you some picture, but as already as the speaker has indicated, one has to look into country differences in order to be able to understand what's happening in the countries specifically.

231
00:24:19,259 --> 00:24:30,079
[SPEAKER_00] In recent months, European policymakers has often and with a lot of praise referred to resilient labor markets.

232
00:24:30,920 --> 00:24:50,000
[SPEAKER_00] The commissioner, when he presented the forecast on the 15th of May, also President Lagarde, on various occasions on the press conferences, was referring to resilient labor markets, which were welcome because they supported household spending and confidence.

233
00:24:51,680 --> 00:25:02,660
[SPEAKER_00] In the same way, I shared that view, but I was always a little bit irritated because nobody was really defining what are you meaning by resilience, what are you measuring, what is the concept that you are using.

234
00:25:02,660 --> 00:25:14,180
[SPEAKER_00] And so I will start very briefly, only two slides, and I will very quickly go over it, but just to place a little bit what is labor market resilience and what is not according to me.

235
00:25:14,680 --> 00:25:31,519
[SPEAKER_00] Then I will look into a number of topical issues on the labor market, the employment situation after COVID, the personal coexistence of tightness and slack, and then wage developments, how they are, and then a number of concluding remarks.

236
00:25:31,519 --> 00:25:41,220
[SPEAKER_00] On the concept of labor market resilience, in science, there is a very long history of the word resilience.

237
00:25:41,220 --> 00:25:56,180
[SPEAKER_00] It is used very long and very detailed in physics and engineering and psychology, but it has, the term resilience has become fashionable by policy makers in Europe since Euro area crisis.

238
00:25:56,180 --> 00:26:07,700
[SPEAKER_00] To some extent, in my view, it's worth otherwise than using flexibility or structural reforms, and so the resilience term, to some extent, was useful to that extent.

239
00:26:08,539 --> 00:26:22,700
[SPEAKER_00] In economic terms, economic resilience refers to the ability of a country to withstand adverse shocks and to recover quickly to potential after adverse shocks.

240
00:26:22,700 --> 00:26:25,500
[SPEAKER_00] That is the general definition of economic resilience.

241
00:26:25,500 --> 00:26:37,140
[SPEAKER_00] Labor market resilience, on the contrary, I haven't found a shared definition or even a general shared understanding of what is meant by labor market resilience in the literature.

242
00:26:37,140 --> 00:26:38,140
[SPEAKER_00] Again, I'm not a specialist.

243
00:26:38,140 --> 00:26:43,380
[SPEAKER_00] I only have a week or two to look into that, but so if it exists, it's fine.

244
00:26:43,380 --> 00:26:47,380
[SPEAKER_00] But the principle one can distinguish between two concepts.

245
00:26:47,380 --> 00:27:06,779
[SPEAKER_00] One, which is very broad and is essentially due to the OECD, a seminal paper of 2014, where they have a very excellent paper, and where they defined the capacity, labor market resilience, as the capacity of the economy to limit persistent deviations from output and labor outcomes.

246
00:27:06,779 --> 00:27:11,180
[SPEAKER_00] From pre-crisis trends and aftermath of adverse economic shocks.

247
00:27:11,180 --> 00:27:24,019
[SPEAKER_00] That is a very broad definition, which I'm not very keen of, because you are mixing various elements, and in particular, you are mixing policies with labor market functioning.

248
00:27:24,019 --> 00:27:38,180
[SPEAKER_00] And so I'm much more in favor of the more strict definition of resilience, which is the capacity of the labor market itself, independent of any policy support or withdrawal, to adapt and respond to economic shocks.

249
00:27:38,420 --> 00:27:45,220
[SPEAKER_00] I come back to this at the very end, and I will also explain the title, somewhat provocative subtitle, of my presentation.

250
00:27:45,220 --> 00:27:54,259
[SPEAKER_00] I will go very quickly over the next two slides, just a theoretical consideration on labor market resilience and how to define it and how to look into that.

251
00:27:54,259 --> 00:28:08,180
[SPEAKER_00] From a political economy perspective, the extent to which the labor market is regulated and in the way it is managed influences the resilience of the economy.

252
00:28:08,180 --> 00:28:20,500
[SPEAKER_00] And here, these slides present very simplistically and very generally, two types of labor market models, a competitive model and the cooperative model.

253
00:28:21,700 --> 00:28:34,180
[SPEAKER_00] The competitive model argues that the institutional framework should formally and primarily be based on market principles of labor and supply.

254
00:28:34,180 --> 00:28:42,579
[SPEAKER_00] And so this school of thought attaches a lot of importance to flexibility and deregulation of institutions, and certainly of the labor market.

255
00:28:42,579 --> 00:28:51,619
[SPEAKER_00] The other concept is cooperative model, and it's much more on the way mechanisms are foreseen and required in the labor market,

256
00:28:51,619 --> 00:28:58,500
[SPEAKER_00] to protect workers from structural inequalities in the relative power of the different shareholders in the market.

257
00:28:58,500 --> 00:29:01,619
[SPEAKER_00] I will not go into the details and further explanations of that.

258
00:29:01,619 --> 00:29:04,339
[SPEAKER_00] I'm happy to do that overrange with those who are interested.

259
00:29:04,339 --> 00:29:13,700
[SPEAKER_00] There is an ongoing, very rich debate academically and politically on these two concepts, and to what extent one has more merits than the other.

260
00:29:13,700 --> 00:29:15,619
[SPEAKER_00] But that is not the purpose of the discussion today.

261
00:29:15,619 --> 00:29:21,539
[SPEAKER_00] What is important from this discussion is that, in principle, you need to take the two schools of thoughts.

262
00:29:21,539 --> 00:29:26,420
[SPEAKER_00] What they say, and then look into the variables that determine labor market resilience.

263
00:29:26,420 --> 00:29:33,299
[SPEAKER_00] And so here, this table, schematically, gives you three indications.

264
00:29:33,299 --> 00:29:37,220
[SPEAKER_00] Institutional structure, socioeconomic structure, and demographic context.

265
00:29:37,220 --> 00:29:43,940
[SPEAKER_00] All of these variables, in principle, have one way or another a bearing on the resilience of the labor market.

266
00:29:44,900 --> 00:29:46,660
[SPEAKER_00] I will not go into the details here.

267
00:29:46,660 --> 00:29:59,619
[SPEAKER_00] Very, very roughly, I could say that the first category in the last couple of, over the last decade, there has been quite a number of improvements in the institutional structure in European countries.

268
00:29:59,619 --> 00:30:11,380
[SPEAKER_00] So, which would suggest to have some improved resilience, and that's certainly true in the crisis countries, where there has been quite a lot of labor market reforms, to a lesser extent in other countries.

269
00:30:11,380 --> 00:30:18,819
[SPEAKER_00] While on the other two factors, socioeconomic and demographic factors, the outcome is more mixed, and you have improvements and deteriorations.

270
00:30:18,819 --> 00:30:23,700
[SPEAKER_00] So, just this to put a little bit in the framework of resilience.

271
00:30:23,700 --> 00:30:27,779
[SPEAKER_00] Let me now move to a number of developments in the labor market in the EU.

272
00:30:27,779 --> 00:30:31,539
[SPEAKER_00] And the first one is developments in employment.

273
00:30:32,259 --> 00:30:40,819
[SPEAKER_00] The left handslide is employment and unemployment in millions, so it's not in percentages, it's in millions.

274
00:30:40,819 --> 00:30:56,420
[SPEAKER_00] And the graphs indicate that after the widespread job retention schemes that shielded workers from a pronounced slowdown in 2020, the labor market rebounds quite strongly after the pandemic.

275
00:30:57,059 --> 00:31:05,859
[SPEAKER_00] It also indicates that despite the weakening of economic activity towards the end of 2021, unemployment again rebounded.

276
00:31:05,859 --> 00:31:09,460
[SPEAKER_00] The same is true for unemployment.

277
00:31:09,460 --> 00:31:16,019
[SPEAKER_00] You can see that employment slightly increased, but not that much, and then rapidly came down.

278
00:31:16,019 --> 00:31:24,259
[SPEAKER_00] That development in the labor market over the last couple of years is quite different from the period after the 2008 crisis,

279
00:31:24,259 --> 00:31:31,299
[SPEAKER_00] where it took six years in order to achieve employment and unemployment levels of before the crisis.

280
00:31:31,299 --> 00:31:38,180
[SPEAKER_00] And here, already in late 2022, we achieved again the levels of employment and unemployment that we had.

281
00:31:38,180 --> 00:31:40,500
[SPEAKER_00] So, that's the positive picture.

282
00:31:40,500 --> 00:31:47,299
[SPEAKER_00] The somewhat less positive picture is indicated with a dotted line, and the dotted line gives the

283
00:31:48,099 --> 00:31:58,019
[SPEAKER_00] trend increase in employment and unemployment, the trend over 2013-2018, and what if that would have been continued without the pandemic.

284
00:31:58,019 --> 00:32:08,339
[SPEAKER_00] And there you can see that in terms of employment, we are still around 3 million of persons employed less than the trend would have suggested.

285
00:32:08,339 --> 00:32:14,339
[SPEAKER_00] So, we have not yet fully recovered from the pandemic, and also unemployment has not yet fully recovered.

286
00:32:14,339 --> 00:32:23,700
[SPEAKER_00] It has come down to 6%, but has not recovered to and still 1.6 million more than the trend would have suggested without the pandemic.

287
00:32:23,700 --> 00:32:27,940
[SPEAKER_00] So, from that perspective, it's positive.

288
00:32:27,940 --> 00:32:34,980
[SPEAKER_00] It's also positive that we no longer have this ratcheting effect of unemployment, that after every crisis, unemployment gets higher.

289
00:32:34,980 --> 00:32:37,059
[SPEAKER_00] That was in the '80s and the '90s the case.

290
00:32:37,059 --> 00:32:41,940
[SPEAKER_00] So, from that perspective, we have seen quite a more resilient labor market than we have seen before.

291
00:32:42,500 --> 00:32:53,700
[SPEAKER_00] Let's move to the vacancy rates, and here the graph you can indicate, you can see that despite the slowdown, we have a very strong increase in vacancy rates over the last couple of years.

292
00:32:53,700 --> 00:33:10,819
[SPEAKER_00] There has been a very slow and small reduction at the end of 2022, and from that perspective, we can see that a high vacancy rate can act as a buffer for unemployment in terms of, over in times of economic crisis.

293
00:33:10,819 --> 00:33:19,140
[SPEAKER_00] This questioning effect from vacancies only functions to the extent that the labor market works efficiently.

294
00:33:19,140 --> 00:33:24,500
[SPEAKER_00] If that is not the case, then you will not have this dampening effect from vacancies on unemployment.

295
00:33:24,500 --> 00:33:39,460
[SPEAKER_00] Already, the chair has referred to the beverage curve, and that's the standard model or the standard concept to look into

296
00:33:40,819 --> 00:33:45,460
[SPEAKER_00] the efficiency and the degree of mid-smatch in the labor market.

297
00:33:45,460 --> 00:33:52,740
[SPEAKER_00] So, the labor, the beverage curve, the relationship between unemployment and vacancies, or labor shortages.

298
00:33:52,740 --> 00:33:55,299
[SPEAKER_00] Here is labor shortages, but that's the same as vacancy rate.

299
00:33:55,299 --> 00:34:04,420
[SPEAKER_00] And what we can see here is that over, during the previous crisis, these are the blue dotted lines,

300
00:34:04,500 --> 00:34:10,980
[SPEAKER_00] we got an outward shift in the beverage curve, which means that it was deterioration in the match on the labor market.

301
00:34:10,980 --> 00:34:20,340
[SPEAKER_00] Now, in the latest couple of years, which are the gray dots, and it's somewhat shown by the green line,

302
00:34:20,340 --> 00:34:25,940
[SPEAKER_00] we can see that there is no outward movement of the of the beverage curve during the last couple of years.

303
00:34:25,940 --> 00:34:33,059
[SPEAKER_00] So, which is indicative that there has been no structural mismatch over the last couple of years in the European labor market.

304
00:34:33,059 --> 00:34:38,900
[SPEAKER_00] If there were, if there would have been a deterioration, then we would have followed the upper blue line.

305
00:34:38,900 --> 00:34:46,260
[SPEAKER_00] That would have been the beverage curve in terms of mismatches or important mismatches in the labor market.

306
00:34:46,260 --> 00:34:56,980
[SPEAKER_00] So, again, that's a positive development that we have seen, but again, we have high vacancy ratios with an unemployment rate of still around 6%.

307
00:34:56,980 --> 00:35:01,699
[SPEAKER_00] So, which is suggestive of, nevertheless, some structural problems in the labor market.

308
00:35:01,699 --> 00:35:07,300
[SPEAKER_00] Let's move to wages, and also previous speakers have already referred to wages.

309
00:35:07,300 --> 00:35:13,139
[SPEAKER_00] So, here we can see different measures of wages over the cycle.

310
00:35:13,139 --> 00:35:15,460
[SPEAKER_00] Two graphs are from the ECB.

311
00:35:16,260 --> 00:35:22,099
[SPEAKER_00] The most interesting one is on the right hand side, which gives the dryness of wage growth in the Euro area.

312
00:35:22,099 --> 00:35:29,699
[SPEAKER_00] And the graph shows deviations from a model implied trend.

313
00:35:29,699 --> 00:35:37,860
[SPEAKER_00] So, what you see here, the blue line is a wage compensation per head, and you can see that it is below what the model would have suggested.

314
00:35:37,860 --> 00:35:42,420
[SPEAKER_00] So, wage growth has been sluggish compared to what the model would have suggested.

315
00:35:43,059 --> 00:35:49,619
[SPEAKER_00] And then the model is used to look into the determinants of this slugginess in wage growth.

316
00:35:49,619 --> 00:35:57,139
[SPEAKER_00] And here, three factors are important.

317
00:35:57,139 --> 00:36:01,300
[SPEAKER_00] And you can see that the blue column was very important during the period 2013 to 2016.

318
00:36:01,300 --> 00:36:10,739
[SPEAKER_00] So, during that period, labor slack in the European Union affected a negative impact on wage developments in Europe.

319
00:36:11,460 --> 00:36:23,059
[SPEAKER_00] The second element is past inflation, which is the red bar, and here you can see that past inflation became an important driver as of 2016.

320
00:36:23,699 --> 00:36:36,340
[SPEAKER_00] And going further, up to 2018, it stops, but you can see that it was a very important driver of the last couple of years, although it dissipated with the impact in the latter years.

321
00:36:36,340 --> 00:36:41,059
[SPEAKER_00] We'll come back later on at the end to what it would imply for the current situation.

322
00:36:41,059 --> 00:36:52,179
[SPEAKER_00] And then you have productivity growth, and there you can see that productivity growth has only had a very minor impact on wage developments in the European Union.

323
00:36:53,619 --> 00:37:04,579
[SPEAKER_00] So, what does this mean, this wage developments for European labor share?

324
00:37:06,260 --> 00:37:29,619
[SPEAKER_00] Because on top of low productivity growth, low inflation, and substantial labor markets lag, there is strong empirical literature which indicates that technological advance and internationalization of goods and services is also impacting on wage development and on the labor share.

325
00:37:30,019 --> 00:37:37,539
[SPEAKER_00] The labor share is an issue which has been discussed for potentially two centuries, starting with both this law, so I will not go that long.

